<p>China’s defence ministry said it is investigating two of the country’s most senior military leaders, Central Military Commission members Zhang Youxia and Liu Zhenli, for suspected “serious violations of discipline and law”. The move extends a broader anti-corruption drive that has repeatedly reshaped the People’s Liberation Army’s top ranks in recent years, reinforcing President Xi Jinping’s emphasis on discipline inside the armed forces. Outside China, analysts and regional officials are watching closely because abrupt leadership changes could affect military readiness and cross-strait stability, even as Beijing has not publicly detailed the evidence behind the cases.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/40MmSINJLuccu7e4jvq30TPjwpGdL22II3yVk8GOGUPbEIKWMWP0OJb_TYrj6lONTTLn6XgqZr2e8krkkXELSq7phX-7S5kzBupNe_woVHdc30vma4vAr8YZQUl1ALsewswq8FOC67TVbkkuUAPSFQvaBvlXmmj1I73xuANuvN9SsNHCxi4hKX8iBuxokbfqM52unQh90BZS1WQ' alt='Zhang Youxia at a legislative meeting in Beijing in March.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Taiwan monitoring: Taiwan’s defence minister Wellington Koo described the leadership changes in China’s military as “abnormal,” said Taipei is monitoring developments closely, and warned it would not lower its guard given what he called a high level of threat from Beijing.</li><li>Allegation reports: Some outlets reported unconfirmed claims that Zhang was accused of leaking sensitive nuclear-related information to the United States, while noting Beijing has not confirmed those allegations.</li><li>Power dynamics: Zhang, a combat veteran long seen as a key figure in Xi’s military overhaul, is portrayed by one account as a striking example of how quickly standing can change within China’s political-military system.</li><li>Readiness questions: One analysis said repeated removals and investigations among senior officers can disrupt command continuity and complicate planning, which could matter for how China manages its forces and signals toward Taiwan.</li><li>Discipline messaging: A PLA Daily editorial cited by Global Times said officials found corrupt would be handled “without leniency,” emphasizing that rank will not shield people from punishment.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>China’s defence ministry: It announced Zhang Youxia and Liu Zhenli are suspected of “serious violations of discipline and law,” without providing detailed evidence in the initial statement. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/plus/news/china/politics/article/3341261/chinas-top-general-ousted-corruption-investigation'>South China Morning Post</a>)</li><li>Taiwan government: It said it is closely tracking leadership shifts in the PLA, calling the changes “abnormal” and saying Taiwan will remain vigilant. (<a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/chinas-military-crackdown-abnormal-watching-xis-moves-closely-taiwan-13972650.html'>Firstpost</a>)</li><li>Western analysts (as cited): Analysts quoted in coverage suggested the investigations may reflect political consolidation as Xi clears out senior ranks, beyond a purely administrative anti-graft effort. (<a href='https://www.npr.org/2026/01/26/nx-s1-5687896/chinas-top-generals-under-investigation-as-countrys-leader-clears-out-ranks'>NPR</a>)</li><li>China state-linked commentary (as cited): State-linked messaging emphasized a hard line on corruption and argued discipline enforcement applies regardless of seniority. (<a href='https://www.rt.com/news/631501-china-launches-investigation-into-general/'>RT</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/26/world/asia/china-xi-zhang-youxia-military.html'>In Xi’s China, Top General’s Fall Shows Precariousness of Power</a> - nytimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/chinas-military-crackdown-abnormal-watching-xis-moves-closely-taiwan-13972650.html'>China’s military crackdown ‘abnormal’, watching Xi’s moves closely: Taiwan</a> - firstpost.com</li><li><a href='https://www.scmp.com/plus/news/china/politics/